04819nam a22008775i 9780520914032DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209140327 a10.1525/97805209140322doi  a(DE-B1597)543258  a(OCoLC)1149503723  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aF1408.3b.V36 1994eb 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a9802201 aVeliz, Claudio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe New World of the Gothic Fox :bCulture and Economy in English and Spanish America /cClaudio Veliz.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- tI. Prefatory Metaphors -- tII. The Invention of the Indies -- tIII. The Spanish Counter-Reformation -- tIV. Baroque Hedgehogs -- tV. Gothic Foxes -- tVI. Hellenistic Aftermath -- tVII. A World Made in English -- tVIII. The Culture of the Latin American Economy -- tIX. The Crumbling Dome -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aClaudio Véliz adopts the provocative metaphor of foxes and hedgehogs that Isaiah Berlin used to describe opposite types of thinkers. Applying this metaphor to modern culture, economic systems, and the history of the New World, Véliz provides an original and lively approach to understanding the development of English and Spanish America over the past 500 years.According to Véliz, the dominant cultural achievements of Europe's English- and Spanish-speaking peoples have been the Industrial Revolution and the Counter-Reformation, respectively. These overwhelming cultural constructions have strongly influenced the subsequent historical developments of their great cultural outposts in North and South America. The British brought to the New World a stubborn ability to thrive on diversity and change that was entirely consistent with their vernacular Gothic style. The Iberians, by contrast, brought a cultural tradition shaped like a vast baroque dome, a monument to their successful attempt to arrest the changes that threatened their imperial moment.Véliz writes with erudition and wit, using a multitude of sources—historians and classical sociologists, Greek philosophers, today's newspaper sports pages, and modern literature—to support a novel explanation of the prosperity and expanding cultural influence of the gothic fox and the economic and cultural decline endured by the baroque hedgehog.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aComparative civilization. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  abaroque mindset.  abritish empire.  acolonization.  acounter reformation.  acultural achievements.  acultural constructions.  acultural decline.  acultural studies.  acultural traditions.  aculture.  aeconomic systems.  aeconomics.  aeconomy.  aenglish america.  ahistorical developments.  aimperialism.  aindustrial revolution.  alatin american history.  amodern culture.  anorth america.  aphilosophy.  asociology.  asouth america.  aspanish america.  athe new world.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052008316540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520914032?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520914032423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520914032/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY